#read data and save this to an object called bookhappy
bookhappy <- read.csv("BookHappiness.csv", header=TRUE)


names(bookhappy)
#One called book and the other called happy. When we view the data by opening
#it, we notice happy is a score and therefore a continuous variable, while happy
#seems to be a categorical variable.

#to obtain the categories saved to book:
table(bookhappy$book)
#there are 10 books labeled under 1 and 10 books labeled under 2

#We want to be able to not only convert book into a categorical variable (a
#factor variable) but also want to assign a new label in place of 1 and 2. We
#can achieve both of these with one step. In the following code notice we now
#use factor instead of as.factor and this is because we will simultaneously ask
#for new labels to replace the old labels. The levels command will allow the
#user to set the original levels of the variable, and because we are providing
#more than one level these are specified as a list using the concatenate
#function c(). The labels function allows us to specify the new labels we want
#to assign, where the first label directly will correspond to the first level,
#etc.
#Additionally, we are requesting that RStudio overwrite the original unfactored
#and unlabeled variable with its factored and re-labeled version and save it to
#the data under book via the accessor operator $.
bookhappy$book <- factor(bookhappy$book, levels=c(1:2), 
                         labels=c("Book 1", "Book2"))


#Viewing the data shows that the variable book has now been factored and
#relabeled to "Book1" and "Book2" Additionally, we also notice that the data
#seems to have Book1 information stacked on top of Book2; therefore making it a
#long dataset: Where we can think of the book variable as the index variable
#indexing the different book and the happy variable containing the value or
#score directly related to that book.
bookhappy$book
#It is also understood from the problem description that different observations
#read Book1 than those that read Book2, making these independent from each
#other.

#The problem we are tasked with solving is whether the average happiness score
#differs by book. Anytime that we are asked to compare means of two independent
#groups, our first thought should be a two sample independent t-test provided
#the assumptions are met.

#Therefore, before we proceed with running a two sample independent t-test, we
#first check if the assumptions for running such a test are met: 1. normality
#and 2. homogeneity of variance.

#To check normality assumption, because we have two groups and therefore two
#averages, we seek the normality of the differences of these averages The first
#step is to create a variable that will store the differences of the two
#happiness scores (those associated with Book1 and those associated with Book2)

#We notice however that our dataset is shaped long and it would be much easier
#to create this difference variable if our dataset was shaped wide. Let's use
#some of the information learned from previous modules to shape our data to wide

#We use the unstack() base R function
wide_bookhappy <- unstack(bookhappy, happy ~ book)

#Results show 2 columns: Book.1 and Book2 that contain the corresponding happy
#scores (Notice the naming for the books is a bit different Book.1 and Book2)
wide_bookhappy

#Create a difference variable of these scores between the two books, and store
#in the wide_bookhappy data
wide_bookhappy$diffvar <- wide_bookhappy$Book.1 - wide_bookhappy$Book2

#When we view our data, we notice that the diffvar has been placed in the data
#and contains both positive and negative differences indicating that at times
#the happiness score was higher for Book1 and at other times higher for Book2
wide_bookhappy

#There are several ways that we can assess normality in RStudio. We will discuss
#two ways. The first way is via one of the functions we have already learned
#about: stat.desc() within the pastecs package. First we call in the pastecs
#package 
#(Note1: that if it outputs an error at this stage, it might require for the
#re-installation of the pastecs package if you have started a new workspace;
#Note2: if you receive a message in the console that states that objects are
#masked. Remember that R is developed by an open source community and therefore
#not uncommon that multiple packages may use the same name for a function or
#dataset. If you load packages that use the same name for an object, R will warn
#that certain object(s) have been masked).
library(pastecs)

#Using the stat.desc function and this time adding the option norm=TRUE will
#assess the variable specified for normality.
#Some tips:
#By setting basic=TRUE we are asking R to output basic information such as n
#(number of observations) for each variable in our dataset 

#By setting desc=TRUE we are asking R to output descriptive information such as
#mean, median, mode, etc, for each variable in our dataset 

#By setting norm=TRUE we are asking R to output descriptive information such as
#the statistic that tests for normality (Shapiro-Wilks) - normtest.W  and its
#associated p-value (normtest.p). 
#Note: The Shapiro–Wilk test is more appropriate method for small sample sizes (
#<50 samples ) We will focus on this one.
stat.desc(wide_bookhappy$diffvar, basic=TRUE, desc=TRUE, norm=TRUE)

#Results show that the p-value which is stored under normtest.p equals 0.042.
#For this part of the analysis, testing normality has its own Null and
#Alternative hypothesis. 
#Null Hypothesis (H0): data is normal vs. Alternative Hypothesis (Ha): data is
#not normal The p-value outputted under this normality test is 0.042; it is less
#than 0.05 (our default Type I error (alpha)). Therefore, we reject our Null
#Hypothesis and conclude happy is not normally distributed. If we stop here, we
#are not able to proceed with a t-test. When we encounter things like these, it
#is indicative that the sample was not drawn from a population that was normally
#distributed. One approach is to see if we could find an appropriate
#transformation for the variables, recompute the difference, and re-test for
#normality.

#One such common transformation is the squared function. This simply means you
#will create two other variables that store the square of the original book
#variables (Note: the asterisk * is our multiplication operator):
  
wide_bookhappy$Book1_sq <- wide_bookhappy$Book.1 * wide_bookhappy$Book.1

wide_bookhappy$Book2_sq <- wide_bookhappy$Book2 * wide_bookhappy$Book2

#Then we find the difference of these two new squared variables and store under
#a variable called diffofsquares
wide_bookhappy$diffofsquares <- wide_bookhappy$Book1_sq - wide_bookhappy$Book2_sq 

#Data now show that the data now contains three additional variables: each book
#squared and the difference of the squares
wide_bookhappy

#This time, we assess normality of the diffofsquares variable:
stat.desc(wide_bookhappy$diffofsquares, basic=TRUE, desc=TRUE, norm=TRUE)
#Results show that the p-value = 0.0515, and following the same approach as
#before, compare it to the default alpha of 0.05. The p-value is greater than
#0.05 which leads us to fail to reject the null hypothesis and conclusion that
#the diffofsquares variable is normally distributed.



#The second way to assess for normality is to directly use the shapiro.test()
#function contained in base R
shapiro.test(wide_bookhappy$diffofsquares)
#You will notice that results are consistent.

#Because normality was achieved on the diffofsquares variable rather than the
#diff variable, we must continue using the squared variables in the analysis.
#However,when we interpret results, we must back transform to understand results 
#in the original unit of measurement.


#The next step is assessing for the homogeneity of variance assumption. We will
#assess this using the leveneTest() function stored under the car package 
library(car)

#To use this function, within parenthesis specify the two variables we are
#assessing for constant variance: Book1 and Book2 For this part of the analysis,
#testing for the homogeneity of variance has its own Null and Alternative
#hypothesis. 
#Null Hypothesis (H0): there is constant variance vs. Alternative Hypothesis
#(Ha): there is no constant variance

leveneTest(wide_bookhappy$Book1_sq, wide_bookhappy$Book2_sq)
#Results show a p-value of <2.2e-16 which is really small in comparison to the
#default alpha of 0.05. Therefore, we  reject the null hypothesis of
#constant variance and conclude variances are unequal in happiness
#scores between books.
#Note: you might receive a warning message (not an error about the Book variable
#being coerced into a factor. This is because in an attempt to replicate a
#ttest, one can run a linear model where the independent variable becomes the
#categorical variable book. Because we are using wide data, this will not apply
#here.)


#The goal is to test whether there is a significant difference in the happiness
#score when we compare books. This carries its own null and alternative
#hypothesis: 
#The Null hypothesis (H0) = there is no difference in the means or
#that the difference is equal to 0 
#The Alternative hypothesis (Ha) = there is a difference in the means or that
#the difference is not equal to 0

#First, we should explore whether there is a difference at all, irrespective of
#directionality. For wide data, use the t.test() function using the syntax
#below: 
#t.test(dataname$variablename1,dataname$variablename2, alternative =
#c("two.sided", "less", "greater") , mu = 0, paired = FALSE, var.equal = TRUE,
#conf.level = 0.95, na.action = na.exclude)

#Some information about the syntax: 
#(1) because we are not interested in directionality, alternative should
#be set to two.sided; however because the default is two sided, we will leave
#this blank. 

#(2) mu = 0 implies the difference expected under the null hypothesis. Under the
#null hypothesis we do not expect for these two books to differ and would expect
#this difference to be 0. mu=0 is the default in RStudio and because of this we
#also can leave this part blank

#(3) The 2 sample t-test we are conducting is an independent two sample t-test
#and as such not a paired analysis. We therefore set paired = FALSE

#(4) We found that variances between the two groups were  not homogeneous and as a
#results we set var.equal to FALSE; the default in RStudio is TRUE 

#(5)The type I error is set to 0.05 by default; therefore, conf.level is set to
#0.95; because this is the default, we also leave this blank 

#(6) The default is to exclude any na's and we can also leave this option blank


#Given all of the defaults that we have the option of not specifying, our t-test
#command then becomes:
t.test(wide_bookhappy$Book1_sq, wide_bookhappy$Book2_sq, paired = FALSE, var.equal = FALSE)
#Results show that the corresponding t-test statistic is equal to -2.1974 with a
#corresponding p-value = 0.04. Due to the p-value being less than the default
#type I error of 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis of equality of
#the means and conclude that there is a significant difference between the
#means.
#When we look at the output that also provides the average of Book1 under "mean
#of x" and the average of Book2 under "mean of y", we notice these values are
#rather high from what the actual data was. This is where the transformation
#performed plays a key role: we must back transform or undo the transformation
#to get these back to the original unit of measurement.
#To back transform, we take the square root of each of the displayed means, save
#each to a different object and re-run the object to output the back-transformed
#average.


book1_avg <- sqrt(415.2)

book1_avg


book2_avg <- sqrt(605.6)

book2_avg


#Results now show averages that are more in line with what was expected. The
#average of Book1 happiness score is 20.37 while the average of Book2 happiness
#score is 24.61




#Suppose we are interested in conducting the same t-test using the long data.
#This would require that we run the t-test as a linear model(lm).
#To conduct the t-test using the long data, we will follow the syntax below:
# lm(Outcome ~ GroupVariableName, data = dataname,
#alternative = c("two.sided"), mu = 0, paired = FALSE, var.equal = TRUE,
#conf.level = 0.95, na.action = na.exclude)

#Some information about the syntax: 
#(1) because we are not interested in directionality, alternative should
#be set to two.sided; however because the default is two sided, we will leave
#this blank. 

#(2) mu = 0 implies the difference expected under the null hypothesis. Under the
#null hypothesis we do not expect for these two books to differ and would expect
#this difference to be 0. mu=0 is the default in RStudio and because of this we
#also can leave this part blank

#(3) The 2 sample t-test we are conducting is an independent two sample t-test
#and as such not a paired analysis. We therefore set paired = FALSE

#(4) We found that variances between the two groups were not homogeneous and as a
#results we set var.equal to FALSE; the default in RStudio is TRUE

#(5)The type I error is set to 0.05 by default; therefore, conf.level is set to
#0.95; because this is the default, we also leave this blank 

#(6) The default is to exclude any na's and we can also leave this option blank




library(pastecs)
stat.desc(bookhappy$happy, norm=TRUE)


#Given all of the defaults that we have the option of not specifying, our t-test
#command using the long data then becomes:
results <- lm(happy ~ book, data=bookhappy) #when variances are equal



#to view results
summary(results)

#The output shows a t-test statistic for book2 vs book1 = 2.125 and p-value =
#0.0477 Note that the Null and Alternative Hypothesis are the same as in the
#case of the wide data for assessing group average difference. Null Hypothesis
#(H0): There is no difference between the two groups vs. Alternative Hypothesis
#(Ha): There is a difference between the two groups. 
#The p-value is less than 0.05 (our default alpha); Therefore, the Null
#Hypothesis is rejected and the conclusion is that there is a significant
#difference between the two groups as it relates to associated happiness score.



#If we want to see how our study estimates compare across other similar studies , we could output an effect size. Let's output the corresponding
#effect size.

#Compute the effect size by creating the following effect size equation and
#store it under an object called r, where it is dependent on (1) the t-value for
#the book difference estimate stored under #bookBook2 from output and (2) its
#corresponding df.

#We first set the corresponding values from output under t-value for the
#bookBook2 estimate:
t <- 2.125

#We set the df to 18 (Note for a two sample independent t-test, the 
# df = sample size for first group + sample size for second group - 2)
df <- 18


r <- sqrt(t^2 /(t^2 + df))

r

#output result by rounding to 3 decimal places
round(r,3)

#Using the benchmarks for effect sizes and listed below:
# 0.10 (small effect) - in this case the effect explains 1% of total variance
# 0.30 (medium effect) - in this case the effect explains 9% of total variance
# 0.50 (large effect) - in this case the effect explains 25% of total variance

#The higher the effect, the more generalizable our results

#Our result, r=0.448, is just below 0.5, the threshold
#for a large effect. Therefore, as well as being statistically significant, 
#this effect is medium/large and so represents a substantive finding.




#to view results
plot(results)

#ADDITIONAL
