## 2 Sample Dependent T-Test using Wide Data  ##
################################################


#Suppose the question changes a bit and this time each participant reads BOTH
#books and now the two scores are coming from the same person in each row in the
#wide data. Using the wide data, to address whether there are any significant
#differences in the paired averages we should run a PAIRED T-Test. Similar to
#before, we must still assess for normality but this time on the paired
#difference.

#Similar to before, using the stat.desc function and this time adding the option
#norm=TRUE will assess the variable specified for normality.

#Some tips:
#By setting basic=TRUE we are asking R to output basic information such as n
#(number of observations) for each variable in our dataset 

#By setting desc=TRUE we are asking R to output descriptive information such as
#mean, median, mode, etc, for each variable in our dataset 

#By setting norm=TRUE we are asking R to output descriptive information such as
#the statistic that tests for normality (Shapiro-Wilks) - normtest.W  and its
#associated p-value (normtest.p). 
#Note: The Shapiro–Wilk test is more appropriate method for small sample sizes (
#<50 samples ). We will focus on this one.

stat.desc(wide_bookhappy$diffvar, basic=TRUE, desc=TRUE, norm=TRUE)


#We would follow the same approach as before to test the normality and constant
#variance assumption.

#The goal is to test whether there is a significant difference in the happiness
#score when we compare paired means. This carries its own null and alternative
#hypothesis: 
#The Null hypothesis (H0) = there is no difference in the paired means 
#The Alternative hypothesis (Ha) = there is a difference in the paired means 


#To run a dependent t-test using wide data:
t.test(wide_bookhappy$Book.1, wide_bookhappy$Book2, paired=TRUE)


#Results show a corresponding t-test statistic = -1.7755 and with its associated
#df and p-value = 0.1095 The p-value outputted is not less than 0.05 (default
#alpha value) We fail to reject the Null Hypothesis and conclude there is not a
#significant difference between the two paired means; implying that happiness is
#really not dependent on either book.


#REPORTING OUR RESULTS
#The results show that reading Book1 does not produce
#significantly greater or less happiness than reading Book2 (p-value = 0.1095).




